figure 1cFigureYa182RFSurvimportance muticox1023KM logRank pvalue

Requirement Description

I would like to crowdsource the calculation method for Figure 1c in the article. FigureYa182RFSurv selected genes with relatively high importance, followed by conventional methods like multicox to further reduce the number of genes. However, this paper describes a different approachselecting the model from 1,023 combinations based on the log-rank p-value of the Kaplan-Meier (KM) analysis and the number of genes, which is a distinct style.

https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/jcp.28600 fromhttps://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/jcp.28600

FIGURE 1 Identification of candidate genes and development of an integrated PCGlncRNA signature. (a) Volcano plot displayed the lncRNAs and PCGs of the univariate Cox regression analysis. (b) Random survival forest analysis screened 10 genes. (c) After KaplanMeier analysis of 2 1 = 1,023 combinations, the top 20 signatures were sorted according to the p value of KM. And the signature included five genes that were screened out, for it had a relative big log10 p value and a small number of genes. KM: KaplanMeier; lncRNA: long noncoding RNA; PCG: proteincoding gene

Application scenarios

log-rankp

The core idea is permutation and combination.

Based on the variables screened by random survival forest analysis, gene combinations are evaluated using the log-rank test, and the combination with a significant p-value and a smaller number of genes is selected as the prognostic signature.

# Displays the process
display.progress = function (index, totalN, breakN=20) {
  if ( index %% ceiling(totalN/breakN) == 0  ) {
    cat(paste(round(index*100/totalN), "% ", sep=""))
  }
}

#  
# Load the expression data
mexp <- read.table("brca.mRNA.expr.txt",sep = "\t",header = T,row.names = 1,check.names = F,stringsAsFactors = F)
lexp <- read.table("brca.lncRNA.expr.txt",sep = "\t",header = T,row.names = 1,check.names = F,stringsAsFactors = F)
surv <- read.table("brca.surv.txt",sep = "\t",header = T,row.names = 1,check.names = F,stringsAsFactors = F)

# 
# Samples with both expression and clinical data were extracted
com_sam <- intersect(intersect(colnames(mexp),rownames(surv)),colnames(lexp))
mexp <- mexp[,com_sam]
lexp <- lexp[,com_sam]
surv <- surv[com_sam,]

# 
# Merge expression matrix
expr <- rbind.data.frame(mexp,lexp)

# logz-score
# Removal of non-expressed genes, log transformation, z-score
expr <- expr[rowSums(expr) > 0,]
expr <- as.data.frame(round(t(scale(t(log2(expr + 1)))),3))

Filter out genes associated with OS

cox.pcutoff <- 0.05 # coxp # p-threshold for cox
Coxoutput.OS <- NULL
for (i in 1:nrow(expr)) {
  display.progress(index = i,totalN = nrow(expr)) #  # Shows progress
  
  # 
  # Generate temporary variables to store survival and variable expression values
  tmp <- data.frame(gene = as.numeric(expr[i,]),
                    OS.time = surv[,"OS.time"],
                    OS = surv[,"OS"],
                    stringsAsFactors = F)
  
  # cox
  # Univariate COX proportional hazards model
  cox <- coxph(Surv(OS.time, OS) ~ gene, data = tmp)
  coxSummary = summary(cox)
  
  # coxzwaldtest pHR
  # Generate a cox result data frame including gene name, hazard ratio, z-value, Waldtest p-value, and HR confidence intervals
  Coxoutput.OS=rbind.data.frame(Coxoutput.OS,data.frame(gene=rownames(expr)[i],
                                                        HR=as.numeric(coxSummary$coefficients[,"exp(coef)"]),
                                                        z=as.numeric(coxSummary$coefficients[,"z"]),
                                                        pvalue=as.numeric(coxSummary$coefficients[,"Pr(>|z|)"]),
                                                        lower=as.numeric(coxSummary$conf.int[,3]),
                                                        upper=as.numeric(coxSummary$conf.int[,4]),
                                                        stringsAsFactors = F),
                                stringsAsFactors = F)
}

Random forests are further dimensionally reduced

gene.sel <- Coxoutput.OS[which(Coxoutput.OS$pvalue < cox.pcutoff),"gene"]
tmp <- expr[gene.sel,]

rownames(tmp) <- gsub("-","_",rownames(tmp)) # - # Prevent the occurrence of "-" from causing errors in the program
dt.rf <- cbind.data.frame(surv[,c("OS","OS.time")],t(tmp))

ntree <- 1000
surv.rf <- rfsrc(Surv(OS.time, OS) ~ ., 
                 data = dt.rf, 
                 ntree = ntree,
                 importance = TRUE,
                 seed = 12345678)

Permutations and combinations determine the optimal signature

num.imp <- 10
rel.imp <- sort(surv.rf$importance, decreasing = T)
rel.imp.sel <- rel.imp[1:num.imp] #  # Remove a certain number of genes
names(rel.imp.sel) <- gsub("_","-",names(rel.imp.sel)) #  # Restore the gene name

outTab <- NULL
n.sum <- 0
for (i in 1:num.imp) {
  cat(paste0("combination using ",i," genes...\n"))
  tmp <- utils::combn(names(rel.imp.sel), m=i) #  # Get the permutations and combinations under the current number of genes
  n <- ncol(tmp)
  for (j in 1:n) {
    combgene <- tmp[,j] #  #Take out the gene name for each combination
    combexpr <- cbind.data.frame(t(expr[combgene,]), # cox # Build a database to do multivariate cox
                                 OS.time = surv[,"OS.time"],
                                 OS = surv[,"OS"],
                                 stringsAsFactors = F)
    cox <- coxph(Surv(OS.time, OS) ~ ., data = combexpr)
    coxSummary <- summary(cox)
    coeff <- coxSummary$coefficients[,1] #  # Take out the coefficient
    riskscore <- as.matrix(combexpr[,combgene]) %*% coeff # riskscore # Calculate riskscore
    riskscore <- data.frame(riskscore = as.numeric(riskscore[,1]),
                            group = ifelse(riskscore[,1] > median(riskscore[,1]),"HRisk","LRisk"), #  # Grouped according to median
                            row.names = rownames(riskscore),
                            OS.time = combexpr$OS.time,
                            OS = combexpr$OS,
                            stringsAsFactors = F)
    fitd <- survdiff(Surv(OS.time, OS) ~ group,
                     data = riskscore,
                     na.action = na.exclude)
    p.val <- 1-pchisq(fitd$chisq, length(fitd$n) - 1) # log-rank #log-rank test
    
    outTab <- rbind.data.frame(outTab,
                               data.frame(num.gene = ifelse(i == 1, paste0(i," gene"), paste0(i," genes")), #  # Current number of genes
                                          km.pvalue = p.val, # KMp # KM curve p value
                                          core.gene = paste(combgene,collapse = " | "), #  # Genes under the combination
                                          stringsAsFactors = F),
                               stringsAsFactors = F)
  }
  n.sum <- n + n.sum #  # Check the total number of permutations
}
## combination using 1 genes...
## combination using 2 genes...
## combination using 3 genes...
## combination using 4 genes...
## combination using 5 genes...
## combination using 6 genes...
## combination using 7 genes...
## combination using 8 genes...
## combination using 9 genes...
## combination using 10 genes...
if(n.sum == 2^num.imp-1) { #  # If the sum is not equal, an error is reported
  write.csv(outTab,"combination of important genes with KM pvalues.csv",row.names = F,quote = F)
} else (message("Wrong combination!!!"))

sigpoints <- Coxoutput.OS[which(Coxoutput.OS$pvalue < cox.pcutoff),]
unsigpoints <- Coxoutput.OS[which(Coxoutput.OS$pvalue >= cox.pcutoff),]

pdf("volcano.pdf",width = 5,height = 5)
par(bty = "o", mgp = c(2,.6,0), mar = c(3,3,1,1), las = 1, font.axis = 1) # 
plot(log(Coxoutput.OS$HR),
     -log10(Coxoutput.OS$pvalue),
     xlab = "Univariate Cox coefficient",
     ylab = bquote("-log"[10]~"(P value)"),
     xlim = c(-2,2))
points(log(sigpoints$HR),
       -log10(sigpoints$pvalue),
       col = ggplot2::alpha("#E53435",0.8),
       pch = 19)
points(log(unsigpoints$HR),
       -log10(unsigpoints$pvalue),
       col = ggplot2::alpha("#21498D",0.8),
       pch = 19)
